JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
dyadic stability and individual happiness. The quality of early relationships has been shown to influ-
ence those that occur subsequently in life (Donnellan et al., 2005; Englund et al., 2011). A large body 
of research generally documents that being part of a stable romantic dyad in adulthood, and particu-
larly cohabitation (i.e., married or “living together”), can positively impact adjustment in important 
ways (Musick & Bumpass, 2012), including health (Kiecolt-Glaser & Newton, 2001; e.g., reducing 
cardiovascular risk, Smith et al., 2014), parenting efficacy (Cox et al., 1989), and level of stress (e.g., 
Demir, 2008; Johnson et al., 2012).
Although there is evidence to suggest that adults with psychological disorders, including adults 
with attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), benefit from romantic relationship stability 
(e.g., partners will accommodate for deficits; Eakin et al., 2004), psychopathology is most often 
associated with relationship discord (for a review, see Whisman, 2019). Indeed, discord is common 
in romantic relationships including adults with ADHD (e.g., Barkley et al., 2008; Robin & Payson, 
2002). Conflict in romantic relationships of those with mental health problems is concerning given 
that discord adds incremental risk for developing depressive, anxiety, and substance use disorders 
(for review, see Whisman & Baucom, 2012). Despite prior research underscoring obvious impair-
ment in romantic relationships of adults with ADHD, investigations examining the romantic rela-
tionships of adults with ADHD have stalled. Acknowledging the potential of this work to enhance 
available services for adults with ADHD (for review, see Canu & Wymbs, 2015), and the lack of 
recent progress, we summarize research on ADHD in romantic relationships and provide recom-
mendations for researchers and clinicians interested in finding ways to help couples dealing with 
the adverse effects of ADHD.
ADHD AND DIMENSIONS OF ROMANTIC 
RELATIONSHIP FUNCTIONING
Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by de-
velopmentally inappropriate levels of inattention, hyperactivity, and impulsivity across settings 
(American Psychiatric Association, 2013). In adults, ADHD symptoms are associated with dif-
ficulties in interpersonal functioning, educational/occupational performance, and community ac-
tivities (Barkley et al., 2008). ADHD symptoms and impairment persists into adulthood in the 
majority of adults diagnosed as children (50%–67%; Barkley et al., 2008; Sibley et al., 2017). 
National prevalence rates suggest that ADHD is one of the most common mental health disorders 
in adulthood (2.5%–4.4% of adults in the United States; American Psychiatric Association, 2013; 
Kessler et al., 2006).
There are undoubtedly things to appreciate in having a romantic partner with ADHD. Halverstadt 
(1998) underscores how adults with ADHD often “hyperfocus” on romance, and describes how par-
ticular gifts associated with ADHD (e.g., creativity, humor, spontaneity) strengthen relational bonds 
with romantic partners. Still, the small body of literature on the romantic relationships of adults with 
ADHD demonstrates clear differences in comparison to non-affected peers, with most highlighting 
disadvantages of ADHD for relationships.
Dating
Studies reporting basic dating history information has revealed that young adult heterosexual 
men with ADHD appear to have more lifetime romantic partners than men without ADHD (Canu 
