ADULT ADHD AND ROMANTIC RELATIONSHIPS: WHAT WE KNOW 
AND WHAT WE CAN DO TO HELP
& Carlson, 2007), whereas young adult heterosexual women with ADHD reported having fewer 
lifetime romantic relationships than women without ADHD (Babinski, Pelham, Molina, Gnagy, 
et al., 2011). Researchers have yet to investigate possible explanations for this trend, but one 
plausible reason could be gender-specific partner perceptions of relationship quality. Robin and 
Payson (2002) found that male non-ADHD partners rated their female ADHD partners as dis-
playing more ADHD-related behaviors that negatively impact their relationships than female 
non-ADHD partners reporting on their male ADHD partners. Thus, women with ADHD are in 
relationships with more dissatisfied partners, and thus risk having fewer relationships, while men 
with ADHD may be in relationships with less dissatisfied partners, and could be better positioned 
to initiate or sustain romantic relationships. Notably, young men with the predominantly inatten-
tive presentation of ADHD have been shown to reach dating milestones (e.g., first “steady” dat-
ing partner) at a later age than individuals with the combined presentation of ADHD, who report 
early dating experiences similar to controls (Canu & Carlson, 2003). Those with the inattentive 
presentation also tended to be less verbose during, and less interested in continuing interactions 
with potential love interests (i.e., female confederates). These shy and amotivated behaviors 
may make adults—or at least men—with the inattentive presentation of ADHD less attractive to 
potential mates.
In addition, although not without exception (Sacchetti & Lefler, 2017), ADHD symptoms ­appear 
to be negatively associated with satisfaction in dating relationships. Canu and Carlson (2003) 
showed that female confederates, blind to ADHD status, perceived male college students with 
ADHD-Inattentive Presentation more negatively than peers with ADHD-Combined presentation 
or without ADHD, and were less willing to consider them as a dating partner and even desired 
to continue talking with them less. Bruner et al. (2015) found that college students self-reporting 
clinically significant inattentive and hyperactive-impulsive symptoms reported lower romantic re-
lationship satisfaction than students not reporting clinically significant symptoms of inattention or 
hyperactivity/impulsivity. Similarly, another study revealed a negative association between college 
student-reported inattentive symptoms, but not hyperactive/impulsive symptoms and romantic rela-
tionship satisfaction (Overbey et al., 2011).
Differences in romantic relationship quality between adults with and without ADHD are also 
­exhibited in how they behave with their partners. Bruner et al. (2015) found that college students with 
clinically elevated symptoms of inattention, hyperactivity/impulsivity, or both reported higher levels 
of hostile conflict behavior with their partners than students with no clinically elevated symptoms. 
The same study also reported that students with elevated inattention and hyperactivity/impulsivity 
symptoms had significantly more conflict with their partners than those with elevated symptoms of 
inattention or hyperactivity/impulsivity. Canu et al. (2014) observed and coded behaviors, using the 
Rapid Couples Interaction Scoring System (Gottman, 1996), of young adult couples during a con-
flict resolution task. They found that couples including a partner with ADHD combined presentation 
demonstrated more negative, less positive conflict resolution behavior, and reported lower relational 
satisfaction, than couples including a partner with ADHD inattentive presentation or couples includ-
ing partners with no ADHD diagnosis.
Finally, ADHD also appears to be a risk factor for dating violence. Wymbs, Walther, et al. (2017) 
and Wymbs et al. (2012) found that young adult males diagnosed with ADHD as children reported 
more frequent verbal and physical intimate partner violence (IPV) perpetration than men without 
ADHD histories. Moreover, men and women diagnosed with ADHD as children, especially those with 
elevated current symptoms, are also at greater risk of being victims of IPV (Guendelman et al., 2016; 
Wymbs et al., 2019). Altogether, ADHD has been shown repeatedly to be associated with relationship 
dissatisfaction, conflict, and IPV perpetration and victimization.
