JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
Sexual activity
Adults with ADHD engage in a riskier pattern of sexual behavior than adults without ADHD. 
Specifically, individuals with ADHD initiate sexual intercourse on an average of 1–2 years earlier 
(Barkley et al., 2006; Canu & Carlson, 2003; Donahue et al., 2013; Rokeach & Wiener, 2018), and 
engage in riskier sexual activity (e.g., more partners, less use of contraception, and more casual sexual 
activity) than those without ADHD (Canu & Carlson, 2003; Donahue et al., 2013; Flory et al., 2006; 
Huggins et al., 2015; Rokeach & Wiener, 2018). Flory et al. (2006) theorize that adults with ADHD 
are prone to risky sexual behavior owing to peer factors (e.g., being more likely to associate with peers 
whose attitudes favor involvement in non-conventional activities), family factors (e.g., poor commu-
nication with parents regarding safe sex practices), and the core symptoms of impulsivity interacting 
with the two. Following from this pattern, it is unsurprising that studies have found that adults with 
ADHD are more likely to have unplanned pregnancies and to acquire sexually transmitted diseases 
than adults without ADHD (Barkley et al., 2006, 2008; Flory et al., 2006). Notably, the sexual ac-
tivity of adults with ADHD tends to be especially problematic in those who also have histories of 
comorbid conduct or oppositional defiant disorders (Barkley et al., 2006; Donahue et al., 2013; Flory 
et al., 2006) and those with persistent versus desistent ADHD symptoms and impairment (Barkley 
et al., 2008). Altogether, ADHD is a marker for adults prone to risky sexual behavior and unexpected 
consequences, but those with persistent symptoms and comorbid disruptive behavior problems are at 
greatest risk of both.
Marriage and divorce
Adults with ADHD are found to be less satisfied in their marriages and self-report lower marital 
adjustment than non-diagnosed control groups (Barkley et al., 2008; Biederman et al., 2006; Eakin 
et al., 2004; Minde et al., 2003). Although two studies found that spouses of adults with ADHD report 
somewhat higher relationship satisfaction than their partner with ADHD (Eakin et al., 2004; Minde 
et al., 2003), another study found that spouses of partners with ADHD reported lower intimacy in 
their relationships (Ben-Naim et al., 2017). Eakin et al. (2004) reported that nearly all (96%) spouses 
of adults with ADHD felt their partner's symptoms interfered with their functioning in one or more 
domains (e.g., general household organization/time management, child rearing, and/or communica-
tion) and nearly all (92%) also reported compensating in some way for their partners difficulties. 
These findings extended the work of Robin and Payson (2002), whose survey of romantic partners 
of adults with ADHD revealed that partners identify specific behaviors consistent with symptoms 
of inattention (e.g., not remembering being told things) and hyperactivity-impulsivity (e.g., saying 
things without thinking) that spark discord in their relationships. Acknowledging how common dis-
satisfaction and partner strain is in relationships with adults with ADHD, it is logical that most, but 
not all studies (Weiss & Hechtman, 1993), have found that extramarital affairs (Barkley et al., 2008) 
as well as separation, divorce, and remarriage (Biederman et al., 1993, 2006; Kessler et al., 2006; 
Murphy & Barkley, 1996) occur more frequently in these couples than in relationships of couples 
without ADHD. Delving deeper into the divorce findings, preliminary evidence indicates that women 
with ADHD may be more likely to have divorced than men with ADHD (Minde et al., 2003). In sum, 
marriages including adults with ADHD are more likely to be unsatisfying, a burden for partners, and 
to end in divorce.
