ADULT ADHD AND ROMANTIC RELATIONSHIPS: WHAT WE KNOW 
AND WHAT WE CAN DO TO HELP
PREDICTORS OF ROMANTIC RELATIONSHIP QUALITY 
AMONG ADULTS WITH ADHD
Clearly, the evidence strongly supports deficits in romantic relationship functioning for young 
adults with ADHD. What remains is the important and complex task of identifying distal and 
proximal factors that may clarify who in this group is at highest risk of interpersonal difficulties. 
Identifying distal and proximal predictors of romantic relationship impairment among adults with 
ADHD is sorely needed due to the implications findings from this work may have for dating, 
sexual activity, marriage, and divorce, and overall quality of life. Although the research signals 
group-level social problems, it is the case that some with ADHD fare better than others, at least 
in some contexts, as can be seen in differences between ADHD presentations noted above (e.g., 
Barkley et al., 2006; Canu & Carlson, 2003; Canu et al., 2014; Flory et al., 2006). Nonetheless, 
very few studies have examined distal and proximal risk factors of romantic relational dysfunction 
among adults with ADHD.
Distal predictors
Gender
In their recent review of gender differences in ADHD-related impairment, Williamson and Johnston 
(2015) found 13 studies that have investigated gender as a risk factor in adults with ADHD, but only 
a few included measures of social functioning (e.g., Arcia & Conners, 1998; Fedele et al., 2012). 
Overall, these studies focusing on social impairment suggest that women with ADHD experience 
more interpersonal impairment than men with ADHD. For example, Fedele et al. (2012) found that 
sex moderated the association between ADHD and social impairment, such that female college stu-
dents with ADHD endorsed experiencing more impairment in their general social lives than male col-
lege students with ADHD, while male controls reported more impairment than female controls. The 
authors speculate that the symptoms of ADHD may be more distressing to young women than men, 
who may perceive social/relational deficits as less impairing owing to differential socialization, and 
that women with ADHD may be more accurate reporters of their impairment than men with ADHD. 
However, it should be noted that not all published research is consistent with the trend of these find-
ings. Babinski, Pelham, Molina, Waschbusch, et al. (2011) found that women with ADHD were more 
impaired in their romantic relationships than women without ADHD, but women with ADHD did not 
have more romantic relationship impairment than men with ADHD. Ben-Naim et al. (2017) found that 
female spouses of men with ADHD reported lower intimacy in the relationship than male spouses of 
women with ADHD. Wymbs et al. (2019) and Wymbs, Dawson, Suhr, et al. (2017) tested gender as 
a moderator of the associations between ADHD and IPV perpetration and victimization, and found 
that gender did not moderate the associations between ADHD and IPV. Instead, they demonstrated 
that women (regardless of ADHD status) were more likely than men to report perpetrating and being 
victims of IPV. Taken together, the literature is mixed with regards to gender differences in romantic 
relationship impairment among adults with ADHD, as women appear to have more difficulties than 
men according to some outcomes (e.g., social impairment, divorce), no or less differences on others 
(e.g., intimacy, romantic relationship impairment), or differences that are not necessarily an ADHD-
specific phenomena (e.g., IPV).
6  | 
   
JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
Maltreatment in childhood
Individuals who experience child abuse and/or neglect are at increased risk for adverse romantic rela-
tionship outcomes as adults, including higher rates of relationship termination (i.e., divorce or discon-
tinuation), less positive perceptions of their current romantic partners, more infidelity, and increased 
risk of perpetrating or being victims of IPV than adults without abuse histories (Colman & Widom, 
2004; Whitfield et al., 2003). The apparent connection between childhood maltreatment and romantic 
relationship problems is concerning in light of the fact that adults with ADHD often have histories of 
being maltreated as children (e.g., Ford et al., 2000). However, to our knowledge, only two studies 
have examined maltreatment as a moderator of social difficulties among individuals with ADHD. 
Wymbs, Dawson, Suhr, et al. (2017) and Wymbs et al. (2019) found that self-reported histories of 
childhood maltreatment (composite of emotional, physical, and sexual abuse) did not strengthen the 
association between ADHD and IPV perpetration or victimization. Nonetheless, because it is plausi-
ble that experiencing childhood maltreatment may increase the risk of other dating or romantic rela-
tionship difficulties (e.g., risky sex), additional studies are needed to test whether or not adults with 
ADHD and maltreatment histories are particularly prone to experience relationship distress.
Academic achievement
Having lower educational achievement is associated with a variety of concerning behaviors, includ-
ing dating violence (Moffitt & Caspi, 1999; Thompson et al., 2006), which is concerning given that 
histories of academic underperformance are common in adults with ADHD (Barkley et al., 2008). 
Interestingly, Guendelman et al. (2016) conducted a study to examine the relationship among child-
hood ADHD status, academic achievement, and risk of IPV in a sample of young women followed 
from childhood. Reading and math achievement moderated associations between ADHD and IPV 
victimization in young adulthood, such that women with childhood ADHD who had low academic 
achievement were more likely than those with high achievement, or women without ADHD histories, 
to be victims of assault by romantic partners. The study authors argue that academic achievement, 
specifically lower achievement, likely was a marker for other factors (e.g., low income, affiliating 
with risky partners) that were more proximal risk factors for experiencing victimization. Research is 
needed to replicate this finding, to test additional mediators explaining risk of IPV victimization, and 
to examine whether adults with ADHD and histories of low academic achievement are also at risk of 
experiencing difficulties in other relational domains.
Proximal predictors
Emotion dysregulation
The concept of emotion dysregulation encapsulates problematic characteristics such as emotional 
impulsivity and irritability, impatience, low frustration tolerance, and being easily angered (Barkley 
& Fischer, 2010). Research on the biological and physiological underpinnings of emotion dysregula-
tion underscores its relevance for ADHD. For example, neuroimaging studies have found deficits in 
neural circuits related to inhibitory control and emotional regulation that are particularly common in 
individuals with ADHD (for review, see Gallo & Posner, 2016). Additionally, deficits in the parasym-
pathetic nervous system, specifically issues with inhibiting fight or flight responding during social 
