ADULT ADHD AND ROMANTIC RELATIONSHIPS: WHAT WE KNOW 
AND WHAT WE CAN DO TO HELP
interactions, are also believed to place individuals at risk for emotional liability. Summarizing re-
search related to polyvagal theory (Porges, 1995), Beauchaine (2001) postulates that excessive vagal 
reactivity, specifically reduction in respiratory sinus arrhythmia (RSA; i.e., the degree of ebbing and 
flowing of heart rate during the respiratory cycle) among those with low basal RSA when triggered 
in social situations, is predictive of emotion dysregulation. Moreover, links between RSA reactivity 
and emotion dysregulation have been found in young children with ADHD (Beauchaine et al., 2013), 
albeit not consistently so (Beauchaine et al., 2007). Taken together, it appears that adults with ADHD, 
at least those diagnosed as children, are neurologically and physiologically predisposed to emotion 
dysregulation, although the evidence appears to more consistently support links among neurological 
deficits, ADHD, and emotion dysregulation.
Not surprisingly, having the tendency to express anger, frustration, sadness, or even happiness with 
little or no premeditation may explain the interpersonal difficulties of adults with ADHD, and this 
may begin well before adulthood. For example, Bunford et al. (2018) reported that young adolescents 
with ADHD (Mage = 13.5 years) are more likely to self-report emotion regulation difficulties than 
peers without ADHD, and these difficulties are associated with greater parent- and self-rated social 
impairment, even when controlling for oppositional defiant disorder. In research with young adult 
populations, Bruner et al. (2015) found that college students reporting more clinically elevated symp-
toms of inattention and hyperactivity/impulsivity also reported greater emotion regulation difficulties. 
In turn, self-reported emotion dysregulation was positively associated with self-reported romantic 
relationship dissatisfaction. Two studies have also examined emotion regulation and romantic rela-
tionships in young adults with ADHD (Mage > 27 years). Barkley and Fischer (2010) found that adults 
with ADHD diagnosed in childhood who endorse high emotional impulsivity also tend to report more 
impaired social and romantic relations than adults without ADHD histories or those with low emo-
tional impulsivity. Bodalski et al. (2019) found that self-reported emotion dysregulation mediated the 
association between self-reported ADHD and romantic relationship satisfaction, such that individuals 
reporting more ADHD symptoms also tended to report greater deficits in emotion regulation, which 
in turn were associated with lower self-reported relationship satisfaction. Although the consistency 
