## Key Findings
CONCLUSION
Given that success in romantic relationships is considered by many to be a major developmental task 
and that ADHD persists for many affected individuals into adulthood, research on romantic adjust-
ment of affected adults is surprisingly limited. The majority of existent published research points, 
however, to a robust association between ADHD and negative outcomes such as lower satisfaction 
in relationships, maladaptive conflict resolution styles, higher rates of relational dissolution, and be-
havioral issues such as unsafe sex and IPV. A more limited array of findings and theoretical rationale 
point to some factors that might help us to predict who, among those with ADHD, might be at great-
est risk for difficulties, including distal (i.e., female gender; maltreatment in childhood; academic 
underachievement in adolescence) and proximal (i.e., deficits in emotional dysregulation; problem-
atic alcohol/drug use; partnering with or parenting another with ADHD) variables.... (Extracted from Discussion)

## Methodology
methods and/or informants to test associations among ADHD, emo-
tion dysregulation, and romantic relationship distress.
On a related line of inquiry, Wymbs (2018) examined the role of inhibitory control as a mechanism 
connecting adult ADHD with communication and problem-solving behavior in couples. In this study, 
partners were randomly assigned to either engage in a task meant to reduce their energy needed for be-
havioral self-control (i.e., self-control resource depletion condition) or to engage in a similar task not 
meant to tax their self-control resources (i.e., no depletion condition), and then these adults engaged 
in a problem-solving task with their partners. Results of this experimental manipulation of inhibitory 
control indicated that adults with ADHD, particularly those in the self-control resource depletion con-
dition, communicated less positively and more negatively with their partners than adults with ADHD 
in the no depletion condition and adults without ADHD, regardless of their depletion condition. That 
is, adults with ADHD appear to be more susceptible than adults without ADHD to discordant commu-
nication and problem solving with their partners during moments when their ability to inhibit aversive 
communication behavior is weakened. In summary, there is reason to suspect that emotion dysreg-
ulation, and lack of psychological resources needed to inhibit emotional reactions, increases risk of 
relationship problems among individuals with ADHD. More studies, particularly those assessing key 
concepts with measures beyond self-report ratings, are needed to evaluate whether this a risk pathway 
unique to ADHD or one that is common among all adults with romantic relationship difficulties.
8  | 
   
JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
Psychological comorbidities
One of the hallmark qualities of ADHD is that it commonly co-occurs with other psychological dis-
orders. Frequent comorbidities associated with ADHD in adulthood include substance use disorders, 
antisocial personality disorder, anxiety disorders, and depressive disorders (Barkley et al., 2008). As 
it relates to relationship dysfunction, the regularity of additional mental health disorders among adults 
with ADHD is particularly troubling in light of evidence linking many of these common comorbidi-
ties with numerous indicators of relationship distress (i.e., dissatisfaction, poor communication and 
problem-solving behavior, IPV; for review, see Whisman, 2019). Thus, there is reason to speculate 
that adults with ADHD and one or more comorbid disorders may be at increased risk of relationship 
difficulties.
With that said, it is surprising to see how few studies have examined psychological comorbidities 
as moderators of the association between adult ADHD and interpersonal difficulties. In fact, we were 
only able to identify two studies, and both focused on psychopathic traits, alcohol abuse, and illicit 
drug use as moderators and IPV as the outcome variable (Wymbs, Dawson, Suhr, et al., 2017; Wymbs 
et al., 2019). Results of these studies indicated that both substance use variables moderated associa-
tions between ADHD and IPV, such that young adults with elevated ADHD symptoms who reported 
abusing alcohol or using illicit drugs were at greater risk of IPV perpetration and victimization than 
those with elevated ADHD symptoms who did not report alcohol abuse or illicit drug use. Research 
is needed to disentangle whether these findings point to adults with ADHD being more susceptible 
to IPV when intoxicated, or whether they reflect risk owing to third variables underlying presence of 
ADHD and substance use problems (e.g., shared genetic risk). Psychopathic traits were not observed 
to moderate risk of IPV perpetration in either study, which was surprising in light of the robust asso-
ciations between psychopathy and IPV perpetration in other studies (for review, see Robertson et al., 
2020). This may indicate that psychopathic traits are more relevant in samples with higher levels 
of these traits (e.g., individuals with incarceration histories) than the community samples tested by 
Wymbs and colleagues. Altogether, although these studies underscore alcohol abuse and illicit drugs 
as moderators of the association between ADHD and IPV, there remains a need for studies to exam-
ine whether additional psychological comorbidities (e.g., depression, anxiety) strengthen or weaken 
associations between ADHD and broader domains of relationship dysfunction (e.g., communication 
and problem-solving skills).
Partner behavior
Existing investigations of romantic relationships involving adults with ADHD have largely had a 
singular focus: assessing the qualities of the adults with ADHD that increase the risk of maladaptive 
outcomes. This line of inquiry is logical, but ignores the possibility that qualities of their partners also 
contribute to the relationship difficulties. With few exceptions (e.g., when romantic partners share 
substance use problems; for review, see Whisman & Baucom, 2012), the broader relationship litera-
ture is replete with studies highlighting the role of both partners in facilitating relationship problems 
(e.g., violence: Montesino et al., 2015).
In light of evidence indicating that adults with similar traits are attracted to one another more fre-
quently than would be expected by chance, a phenomenon known as assortative mating (Boomsma 
et al., 2010; van Grootheest et al., 2008), one characteristic worth considering as a contributor to re-
lationship distress is partner ADHD. As previously discussed, ADHD is a risk factor for relationship 
difficulties, and one could speculate that having two partners with ADHD may further increase risk of 
      |  9
ADULT ADHD AND ROMANTIC RELATIONSHIPS: WHAT WE KNOW 
AND WHAT WE CAN DO TO HELP
discordant romantic relations. However, evidence is scarce regarding whether adults with ADHD are 
more likely to partner with other adults with elevated ADHD symptoms or whether adults with ADHD 
in relationships with partners exhibiting similar ADHD profiles are prone to relationship distress.
To our knowledge, there are only two studies that have examined the level of ADHD symptoms 
in partners of adults with ADHD. As part of their small open trial of a novel couples therapy-based 
approach to treating ADHD in adulthood, Wymbs and Molina (2015) reported that 67% of the adults 
with ADHD in their sample had partners with clinically significant ADHD symptoms. The rate of 
clinically elevated ADHD symptoms in their sample suggests that adults with ADHD select part-
ners with elevated ADHD symptoms at rates far above chance. Still, the Wymbs and Molina (2015) 
sample was treatment seeking, and results—including rates of shared ADHD symptoms—may not 
generalize to couples not participating in therapy. In a subsequent study of an online, community 
sample, Steele et al. (in press) found adults diagnosed with ADHD in childhood, especially those 
with elevated current symptoms, reported that their partners had more clinically significant symptoms 
of ADHD than adults without ADHD histories. Notably, the adults with persistent ADHD who had 
partners with elevated ADHD symptoms also tended to report more psychological and physical IPV 
perpetration and victimization than adults without ADHD histories, even among those with partners 
exhibiting elevated ADHD symptoms. Results of this study are limited by fact that participants rated 
their own and their partners ADHD symptoms, without partner input. That said, their findings, par-
ticularly when considered beside the rate of couples with two partners having ADHD in the Wymbs 
and Molina (2015) study, appear to indicate that adults with ADHD, especially those with elevated 
current symptoms, tend to select romantic partners who also exhibit clinically significant symptoms 
of ADHD at higher rates than would be expected by chance, which is suggestive of assortative mating. 
Furthermore, this greater density of ADHD symptoms is associated with greater dysfunction in the 
relationship. Assortative mating patterns underscore the potential for partner behavior to facilitate the 
association between adult ADHD and romantic relationship difficulties, but this bears further empir-
ical investigation.
Having a child with ADHD
ADHD is highly heritable (Gallo & Posner, 2016). A recent study of 37 twin studies indicated that, on 
average, 74% of the variability in the core symptoms of ADHD is explained by genetic transmission 
(Faraone & Larsson, 2019). Given the notable heritability of ADHD, children of parents with ADHD 
are clearly at elevated risk of developing ADHD. We have known for over 25 years that parents diag-
nosed with ADHD, particularly in childhood, are prone to having children with ADHD (Biederman 
et al., 1995), but only recently have researchers examined the risks of raising children with chronic 
disruptive behavior problems for parent couples, including those who have ADHD partners.
Unfortunately, having a child with ADHD may further increase the risk of romantic relational 
discord among adults with ADHD. Wymbs et al. (2008) showed that parents of children with ADHD 
are twice as likely to divorce by the time their child is 8 years old than parents of children without 
ADHD. They further specify that higher levels of disruptive behavior exhibited by children with 
ADHD uniquely predicts early divorce, over and above other putative predictors, including parental 
psychopathology (i.e., parental substance abuse, maternal depression, paternal antisocial behavior), 
but they did not include parental ADHD as a risk factor in this study. Using a confederate child be-
havior manipulation, Wymbs and Pelham (2010) sought to examine whether disruptive child behavior 
causes parents to engage in conflictual communication behavior with each other. Results indicated 
that child ADHD behavior indeed causes parents to argue, as parent couples randomly assigned to 
10  | 
   
JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
manage a school-aged confederate child exhibiting ADHD-like behavior communicated less positively 
and more negatively than couples managing a confederate behaving like a typical child. Secondary 
analyses with the same sample showed that parents with elevated ADHD symptoms were particularly 
susceptible to negative communication with their partners during interactions with ADHD-like con-
federate children (Wymbs, Dawson, Egan, et al., 2017; Wymbs et al., 2015). Interestingly, Wymbs, 
Dawson, Egan, et al. (2017) found that couples with two partners with elevated ADHD symptoms who 
interacted with ADHD-like children were observed to communicate more positively than couples with 
one or no partners with ADHD interacting with ADHD-like children. So, while there is reason to be 
concerned that partners with ADHD may communicate more negatively with each other while man-
aging a child with ADHD, there is some relief to know that these couples may balance their negativity 
with positivity.
In sum, after surveying the literature, it is obvious that individuals with ADHD, especially those 
diagnosed as children, evince substantial interpersonal impairment. Their social impairment persists, 
for most, across interactions with dating partners and spouses. Adults with ADHD are less desirable 
to potential partners, are more likely to experience dissatisfying and conflict-ridden relationships and 
IPV, engage in more risky sexual activities, and are more likely to experience separation or divorce 
than adults without ADHD.
Next steps
While our understanding of the romantic relationship difficulties of adults with ADHD continues to 
grow, clarity is lacking in several respects. First, relatively few longitudinal studies of relationship 
behavior of adults with ADHD have been undertaken. Prospective studies would enhance our under-
standing of the course of relationship dysfunction among adults with ADHD, including contextual 
or interpersonal factors that may precede the onset of relationship difficulties or spark relationship 
discord and dissolution. Daily diary research designs are especially useful for this purpose, as they 
can allow for one to observe how relationship problems develop and unfold in real time in naturalis-
tic settings. For example, researchers using daily diary designs have shown that verbal and physical 
IPV perpetration and victimization are most likely to occur immediately after alcohol consumption 
(Shorey et al., 2014; Testa & Derrick, 2014). If employed in studies of adults with ADHD, find-
ings would have clear implications for how to prevent or treat romantic relationship issues in this 
population.
Second, little is known about who among the large population of adults with ADHD may be es-
pecially at risk for romantic relationship difficulties. We found some evidence in favor of academic 
underachievement in adolescence, alcohol abuse, and illicit drug use in adulthood, and among parents, 
having a child exhibiting ADHD/ODD behavior that increased the risk of relationship impairment in 
adults with ADHD (Guendelman et al., 2016; Wymbs, Dawson, Egan, et al., 2017; Wymbs, Dawson, 
Suhr, et al., 2017; Wymbs et al., 2015, 2019). Gender and history of maltreatment were tested as 
moderators, but were not found to be consistently associated with the strength of associations between 
ADHD and relationship difficulties. Otherwise, we found no empirical inquiries into any other addi-
tional theoretically indicated variables as moderator candidates (e.g., racial/ethnic status, low socio-
economic status, sexual orientation). The likely reason for this gap in the literature is the reliance on 
samples comprised nearly always with Caucasian, heterosexual couples. There is a substantial need 
for research to be conducted with large, diverse samples (e.g., samples overselecting racial/ethnic 
minorities, LGBTQ+adults). Doing so will not only allow for tests to be powered to identify addi-
tional moderators, but will also provide an opportunity to assess important mechanisms underlying 
      |  11
ADULT ADHD AND ROMANTIC RELATIONSHIPS: WHAT WE KNOW 
AND WHAT WE CAN DO TO HELP
the functioning of LGBTQ+and racial/ethnic minority couples (e.g., minority stress theory, systemic 
racial barriers) that could be relevant for minorities diagnosed with ADHD.
Third, there is also a dearth of published studies investigating mediation models explaining the link 
between ADHD and romantic relationship problems. Early work indicates that emotion dysregulation 
(e.g., Bodalski et al., 2019; Bruner et al., 2015) and lacking resources needed for inhibitory control 
(Wymbs, 2018) may operate as mechanisms linking ADHD with romantic relationship difficulties. 
However, outside of the experimental manipulation of inhibitory control, prior work indicating emo-
tion dysregulation operates as a mediator between ADHD and relationship impairment has relied 
on self-report indices of emotion dysregulation as well as ADHD and relationship distress. Until 
additional evidence is compiled from studies ruling out respondent bias as a contributing factor (e.g., 
using computer tasks to assess trait emotion dysregulation; examining RSA reactivity in response to 
triggers during problem-solving task with partners), it is premature to call emotion dysregulation a 
candidate target for interventions seeking to reduce relationship impairment. Furthermore, research 
is needed to identify and test additional mediators as well. To this end, we have recently completed 
an alcohol administration study to examine whether acute alcohol intoxication explains risk of IPV 
perpetration among adults with ADHD. Preliminary results indicate that adults with ADHD in cer-
tain circumstances (e.g., having partners without ADHD, self-reporting histories of IPV perpetration) 
appear prone to alcohol-facilitated IPV (Wymbs et al., 2020). There remains a need to investigate 
plausible mediation mechanisms; such research could be invaluable to identifying intervention targets 
that could reduce IPV and additional relationship problems faced by adults with ADHD.
In addition to our recommendations above, we believe future studies should improve method-
ologically in several ways in order to better inform clinicians and researchers alike regarding the 
link between ADHD and romantic relationship problems. First, many of the above studies relied on 
self-reported ratings for both ADHD diagnosis and relationship functioning. As alluded to earlier, 
this is concerning owing to the potential for informant bias to at least partially explain connections 
between variables. To remedy this, future studies should solicit ratings of ADHD and relationship 
functioning from other informants, with romantic partners perhaps being the most desirable (e.g., 
Wymbs & Molina, 2015), although observational data on relationship functioning would also be key 
(e.g., communication and problem-solving behavior; Canu et al., 2014). Second, most of the above 
studies were conducted with emerging adults (i.e., aged 18–25; Arnett, 2000). Studies are needed to 
evaluate the relationships of older adults with ADHD—including parents—as these may uncover 
different risk factors for, or mechanisms underlying, relationship problems in this population. To this 
end, accessible methods for recruiting samples of adults with ADHD with wider age ranges are avail-
able (e.g., Amazon's Mechanical Turk; Wymbs & Dawson, 2019). Third, clinical trials assessing the 
efficacy of interventions for adult ADHD should test for effects on romantic relationship functioning. 
Some available treatment programs (Safren et al., 2005; Wymbs & Molina, 2015) include partners 
in the intervention, and thus are tailored for collecting relationship outcome data. Fourth, in light of 
recent calls for researchers to more consistently examine for sex and gender differences in psychopa-
thology (Hartung & Lefler, 2019), we recommend that future investigations of ADHD and romantic 
relationships continue to assess the role that sex or gender may play in their findings.
Clinical recommendations
Although much is left to be learned about their romantic relationship difficulties, we know enough to 
make several informed recommendations for clinicians treating couples affected by ADHD. However, 
before addressing ADHD in the context of therapy, it is important to conduct a proper assessment. 
12  | 
   
JOURNAL OF MARITAL AND FAMILY THERAPY
Consistent with available guidelines (Kooij et al., 2019), we recommend screening for ADHD in adult 
clients using the World Health Organization Adult ADHD Self-Report Scale (ASRS; Kessler et al., 
2005). The original ASRS contains items assessing the 18 DSM diagnostic symptoms, and 6 of those 
items have been shown to be an effective screening tool. A more recent version includes updates for 
DSM-5 criteria and a refined 6-item screening (Ustun et al., 2017). Ustun et al. (2017) reported that 
sensitivity and specificity analyses indicate the current ASRS Screener is excellent at distinguish-
ing adults with ADHD from those who do not have ADHD diagnoses. Clients who screen positive 
for ADHD on the ASRS screener could then complete the full ASRS and an empirically supported 
measure of ADHD-relevant impairment (e.g., Adult Impairment Rating Scale; Dawson et al., 2020; 
Weiss Functional Impairment Rating Scale Self-Report; Weiss, 2000) to more thoroughly assess for a 
possible ADHD diagnosis. Additionally, acknowledging the high degree of overlap between ADHD 
and other common mental health disorders in adults, most notably depressive and anxiety disorders, 
we recommend conducting an interview to assist in differential diagnosis as well as to confirm the 
presence of ADHD symptoms and impairment in childhood.
At present, adaptations of cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) have the most empirical support for 
treating ADHD in adults (Knouse et al., 2017; Kooij et al., 2019). CBT for adult ADHD reviews skills 
to improve organization and behavioral self-control as well as strategies to manage stress and harmful 
cognitions perpetuating task avoidance (Ramsay, 2010). In brief, CBT requires the ability to accu-
rately self-monitor and self-regulate without prompting from others. Some forms of CBT for adult 
ADHD include significant others for individual or optional sessions (e.g., Safren et al., 2010; Virta 
et al., 2008), but their role in treatment is minimal. In light of their difficulties with being self-suffi-
cient (Barkley et al., 2008) and recognizing when their behavior is impaired (e.g., Knouse et al., 2005), 
adults with ADHD may not be prepared to make behavioral changes on their own. If romantic partners 
are willing and able to voice their concerns in the moment to adults with elevated ADHD symptoms, 
they could play an important role in helping them recognize when their behavior causes difficulties 
for their relationship (and possibly other domains of functioning), which may increase the likelihood 
of their loved ones with ADHD (and their relationship) improving.
It is well documented that couples therapy (e.g., behavioral couples’ therapy) can effectively ad-
dress psychopathology within the relationship (e.g., major depressive disorder, substance use disor-
ders; Whisman & Baucom, 2012). Unfortunately, evidence supporting couples therapy for ADHD 
lags far behind. To the authors’ knowledge, only one study has evaluated the benefits of treating adults 
with ADHD in the context of couples’ therapy (Wymbs & Molina, 2015). The study team integrated 
core components of CBT for adult ADHD (Safren et al., 2005) while reviewing effective communi-
cation and problem-solving skills with the couple (Markman et al., 2004). Results of this open trial 
indicated positive treatment effects for self- and partner reports of inattention and impulsivity-hyper-
activity symptoms for the individuals with ADHD, as well as less relationship negativity and con-
flict-inducing behaviors. Although several factors limit generalizability of these findings (e.g., small 
sample size, lack of a control group), preliminary data were encouraging and underscore the potential 
benefits of infusing CBT for adults with ADHD into couples therapy.
Summarizing our above recommendations with suggestions we have made previously (Canu et al., 
2014) and as well as from other respected researchers (Kooij et al., 2019) and practitioners (Pera, 
2015), we recommend the following to clinicians seeking to manage adult ADHD in the context of 
treating relationship dysfunction.
First, do a thorough assessment of ADHD, including history of symptoms and impairment while 
ruling out common overlapping diagnoses (e.g., depression, anxiety).
Second, provide psychoeducation on ADHD for both partners, which may lead to greater under-
standing and acceptance of some behavioral concerns adversely affecting the relationship.
      |  13
ADULT ADHD AND ROMANTIC RELATIONSHIPS: WHAT WE KNOW 
AND WHAT WE CAN DO TO HELP
Third, and related to the last point, therapists working with couples including adults with ADHD 
should be mindful of the burden often shouldered by their partners without ADHD. For the sake of 
strengthening the dyad, it may be necessary to offer coping skills to partners to manage moments of 
acute stress owing to their partner's ADHD symptoms (e.g., forgetting date night, frequent interrup-
tions), and to recognize them for their efforts to take on extra responsibilities and tolerance of their 
partner's minor, recurrent stress-inducing behavior.
Fourth, we recommend integrating CBT adapted to address symptoms and impairments associated 
with ADHD in adulthood (e.g., Safren et al., 2005) into the context of ongoing couples’ therapy.
Fifth, there are aspects and developmental stages of romantic relationships that may signal partic-
ular difficulty for couples including a partner with ADHD that therapists could be more aware of and 
adapt intervention to. For instance, couples including partners with ADHD who are raising children 
may be at particular risk given their relatively high rates of divorce (Wymbs et al., 2008) and ob-
served degree of negative communication while supervising a child with ADHD symptoms (Wymbs, 
Dawson, Egan, et al., 2017; Wymbs et al., 2015). Helping such parents to engage in intervention that 
can effectively address child disruptive behavior (e.g., behavioral parent training; see Evans et al., 
2018, for review) may go a long way toward mending any relational strife present in the couple.
Finally, pharmacotherapy, particularly stimulant medication, has proven effective at reducing 
symptoms of ADHD in adults (Kooij et al., 2019). A referral for psychiatric consultation may be 
warranted in the event there is a need for an immediate resolution of symptoms for the sake of the 
relationship.

