## Clinical Significance
CONCLUSION
Given that success in romantic relationships is considered by many to be a major developmental task 
and that ADHD persists for many affected individuals into adulthood, research on romantic adjust-
ment of affected adults is surprisingly limited. The majority of existent published research points, 
however, to a robust association between ADHD and negative outcomes such as lower satisfaction 
in relationships, maladaptive conflict resolution styles, higher rates of relational dissolution, and be-
havioral issues such as unsafe sex and IPV. A more limited array of findings and theoretical rationale 
point to some factors that might help us to predict who, among those with ADHD, might be at great-
est risk for difficulties, including distal (i.e., female gender; maltreatment in childhood; academic 
underachievement in adolescence) and proximal (i.e., deficits in emotional dysregulation; problem-
atic alcohol/drug use; partnering with or parenting another with ADHD) variables. Much remains to 
be discovered, however, and important future directions for research in this area include examining 
romantic relationships in longitudinal studies of ADHD populations, more formal examination of pos-
sible risk factors in mediational models, use of data from non-emerging adults and “other” informant 
reports, and focusing on relational outcomes for LBGTQ+individuals and couples, as well as non-
White groups. It is our fervent hope that the ADHD research community will pursue these topics, and 
that clinicians will employ targeted, empirically based assessment and intervention in their practice 
with adult ADHD clients engaged in romantic relationships. Nothing short of this will provide ad-
equate information and assistance to this group that appears to tend, literally and figuratively, to be 
hurting in their romantic lives.
